      "label": "Transcript",
      "value": "Beaufort 1841 I cannot convey in any way to my dear James the [?] pleasure his letter of the 25th conveyed to my mind I have felt most deeply for you for two years and yet never could summon resolution to say one word to you as you did not say one to me I knew circumstances must have been adverse to your hopes and wishes not to a living creation did I ever breathe what had transpired between us. all I can say is I hope this has given you such a good lesson or rather that you have learned such a good lesson [for it of no use to have lessons given us if we don't learn them] that you will hence forward throw off cold manners which you know I have often told you oft and I can assure you ten times as often deplored because though I did not mind it much being assured of your affection for me I was fully sensible and fully felt that it was a very great disadvantage to you and I beg you will not for a moment think that now you are to be married that it is no longer of any importance but ever bear in mind it was the cause of almost depriving me of the Lady of my choice surely it is to be watched over lest it be of some other serious injury to me through life- - - I beg you will consider very seriously at this time and try to get an interest in Christ Jesus my dear James you may think as treating a cheerful subject in a very serious manner but I assure it is high time to add such serious- [End Page 1] ness to cheerful subjects for it is all that can give happiness below for be assured [marriage is the happiest state to be sure] that is all important to make even that state happy for you will never escape the pain and anxieties of this life be your state and consideration what it may and I am sure you need not go out of your own family to know that think of the family ties which have broken in it and don't let it make you gloomy but remember that \"Religion never was designed\" \"To make our pleasures less\". but really and truly to lift us above in spirit the ills of life and make us derive with submission the glorious joys above at Gods right hand for ever more- - - Give my best love to Maria and tell her all I say for it is as important to her as you I don't mean because I say it but as a truth- she must share much of my affections if she is your choice for you know how much I have always loved you even when you used [crossed out] - - - I don't pretend that all the affection I feel is worth much for I grow old and indifferent every day but I think I will always love you - - - - I am truly sorry for Hetty one or other of the Children is always indisposed but it is ever better than I feared give her a great deal of love- I daresay you thought my last Epistle a queer thing but I was delighted to find neither you or Mr H- had given Mama reason to think you [End Page 2] had been disrespectful don't say any thing about it I wont say any thing about that report for Mama will give it all to Hetty and she can tell you how when and wherefore it came- Uncle Smith writes in love and all I have said for you know his affection for you is thought quite amusing-I must now conclude with much affection JB. Heyward [End Page 3] James B Heyward Esqr. Care of James Ladson [and] Co Charleston So Ca [End Page 4]"
    },
